80. The Municipality maintain a single stockroom with adequate storage space for all materials and a responsible storekeeper be assigned thereat. The stockroom should be secured against pilferage, unauthorized use and protected from deteriorating effects of the elements;
81. The materials in the stockroom should be properly arranged in such a way as to facilitate retrieval when needed and ensure that fresh usable items are always available. Materials should be issued on first in, first out basis;
82. The storekeeper should keep bin cards for each type of article and hang on shelves or bins where the articles are stored. Reconcile bin cards with the stock/property cards maintained by the stock clerk and with the physical count of stocks on hand;
83. The Office of the municipal treasurer should maintain stock cards for each class of article. All receipts, issuances and balances on hand of supplies and materials should be kept up-to-date. The stock cards serve as guide in preparing estimates of the quantity and description of articles needed to avoid overstocking. These also facilitate physical inventory-taking; and
84. Conduct an immediate inventory-taking of all the items, prepare and submit inventory report to the auditor.

The City Accounting Office to expedite the gathering of sufficient      supporting documents to properly effect the adjustments in the Cash in Bank account for the cited 444 reconciling items. For the subsequent periods, the reconciling items should be immediately adjusted/recorded in the books to avoid difficulty of tracing/monitoring the same;
Management to consider instituting legal actions, if warranted, to resolve the long outstanding Deposits in Transit, and;
The City Accounting Office and Treasurer’s Office to coordinate with each other to effect the cancellation of the existing stale checks and the adjustment to the balance of cash in bank account.

We recommended that management take the following actions:
Direct the Inventory Committee to conduct and complete the periodic physical count of inventories and ensure that the corresponding RPCIs are submitted to the COA Auditor for review and validation.;
Expedite the migration of financial accounts to e-NGAS and direct the CAO to fast-track the transition to the e-NGAS system to improve the accuracy, efficiency, and monitoring of inventory record;
Enforce strict compliance with inventory documentation and require all offices and end-users to consistently prepare and submit RIS and Consumption Reports whenever inventories are issued or consumed, ensuring timely submission to the CGSO;
Strengthen CGSO’s role in inventory consolidation and instruct the CGSO to consolidate all submitted RIS, prepare the Summary of Supplies and Materials Issued (SSMI) reports, and ensure their timely submission to the CAO for proper recording;
Require the CAO and CGSO to conduct periodic reconciliation of their inventory records to address discrepancies, improve data accuracy, and strengthen internal controls over asset management;
Augment manpower in both offices to immediately complete the reconciliation and tracing of discrepancies;
Establish adequate controls and procedures to ensure that inventory classifications and accounting treatment remain consistent between the CAO and CGSO records; and
Submit thereafter to the COA Auditor the Journal Entry Vouchers for adjustments in the inventory accounts.

We recommended that management:
Expedite the One-Time Cleansing of PPE account balances in compliance with COA Circular No. 2020-006 (dated January 31, 2020) and allocate necessary funds for its implementation;
Consider consulting government personnel from other LGUs or national agencies that have successfully conducted the One-Time Cleansing to gather insights and strategies for developing an effective Physical Inventory Plan;
Require the CAO and CGSO to conduct regular reconciliation between physical asset counts and accounting records and augment manpower in both offices to immediately complete the reconciliation and tracing of discrepancies;
Establish adequate controls and procedures to ensure that PPE classifications remain consistent between the CAO and CGSO records.

We recommended that management direct the City Accountant to:
Submit immediately the required documents for all transactions listed in Annexes E to G of this report to enable the auditor to continue validating the year-end payables in terms of their existence, correctness, and veracity;
Make an adjusting entry to reverse the Accounts Payable for any claims that are found to be without legal basis, unfounded, or pertain to purchases delivered, received, and inspected in the following year;
Ensure that JEVs for recognizing Accounts Payable are properly supported with the required documentary evidence;
Avoid recording Accounts Payable with incomplete supporting documents; and
Ensure that, as the internal auditor, all required documents are kept securely under the CAO’s custody and are readily available for review and verification by the auditor to prevent delays in the audit process.

We recommended that management require the:
Concerned contractors to expedite the submission of the necessary supporting documents for processing their claims on the unpaid portion of the completed projects;
CEO to furnish copies of the Certificate of 100% Completion and other relevant documents it issues for the projects completed during the period to the CAO;
City Accountant to:
Prepare the necessary accounting entries to: i. Set up Accounts Payable for the value of completed works of the project that remain unpaid; ii. Reclassify the completed projects to their appropriate asset/expense accounts; iii. Transfer the costs of the completed PPE from the Trust Fund to the General Fund; iv. Provide for Depreciation Expense; and
Provide adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that management direct the CAO to:
Revise the presentation of Loans Payable in the financial statements, classifying the current and non-current portions in accordance with IPSAS No. 1, to ensure compliance with accounting standards and enhance the accuracy and transparency of the financial statements;
Submit the amortization schedules that support the revised presentation of Loans Payable, reflecting the current and non-current portions. These schedules should be attached to the submitted year-end financial statements for future periods;
Provide copies of all duly executed loan contracts and agreements for the City’s existing loans to the COA Auditor's Office for further review and verification; and
Provide adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements, particularly regarding the details of creditors, the purpose of the loans, credit terms, due dates, and loan balances for each account.

We recommended that management take the following actions:
The PS-LGU Depot Manager to:
Ensure that billing statements are timely prepared and submitted to the PS-DBM in accordance with the MOA;
Furnish the City Accountant the copies of the duly received billing statements;
Monitor the status of subsequent MOAs entered into between the LGU and PS-DBM to ensure that approval thereof is not delayed;
Monitor thereafter, the status of settlement of the billings and inform the City Accountant for any outstanding unsettled billings beyond the payment period provided in the MOA;
The City Accountant to:
Prepare the necessary JEVs to record the Management Fees for CYs 2020 to 2024 and furnish copies to the COA Auditor for review;
Ensure thereafter that management fees are recorded as receivable and income in the period in which they were earned in accordance with the accrual basis of accounting; and
Make representations and formal requests, confirmations, and/or demand letters to the PS-DBM for the settlement of any unpaid billing statements beyond the payment period provided in the MOA.

We recommended that management take the following actions:
The CAO to:
Ensure thereafter that expenses for foreign travel are properly recorded in the “Traveling Expenses – Foreign” account;
Submit the supporting computation for the DSA, along with a copy of the UNDP DSA rate for the country of destination and a document showing the peso-dollar exchange rate at the time of the cash advance;
Submit the lacking documentary requirement listed in Annex P of this report; and
Ensure thereafter that cash advances and liquidation for foreign travel are fully supported by the documentary requirements outlined in COA Circular No. 2012-001;
Management to:
Secure an unequivocal approval (or disapproval) from the DILG Regional Director for the previously submitted letter-requests for foreign travel, referencing DILG MC No. 2022-147 as the basis for the Regional Director’s duty to act on the LGU’s requests;
Submit justification on the role of each member of the delegation stating with particularity why their presence is necessary for the success of the benchmarking;
Provide updates and copies of correspondences (if any) to the COA Auditor regarding actions taken under recommendation (b). Failure to provide valid travel authority from the appropriate authorized official may result in the entire travel expense being subject to refund; and
Ensure that, for future similar activities, the LGU secure the necessary foreign travel authority from the DILG Regional, clear specifying and justifying in the request the role of each member of the delegation, if any.

We recommended that management:
Request a detailed breakdown of the registration fees paid to the League Chapters;
Direct the City Accountant to:
Expedite the submission of the lacking documents listed in Annex Q to the COA Auditor for review;
Ensure, moving forward, that expenses for foreign travel are properly recorded in the “Traveling Expenses – Foreign” account;
Make certain thereafter that disbursements are fully supported by the documentary requirements outlined in COA Circular No. 2012-001, based on the nature of the expense.

We recommended that management direct the City Accountant to:
Submit to the COA Auditor copies of the demand letters already sent to the persons accountable for the unliquidated cash advances for validation and reference;
Prepare and submit an updated RUCA setting forth the details of the cash advances to facilitate the preparation of the demand letters by the COA Auditor;
Impose the withholding of any payment of money to those who have unsettled cash advances already outstanding as of December 31, 2011 in light of the final demand made by COA under its Circular No. 2012-004y;
Exert efforts in the verification of the noted negative balances for possible adjustments;
Submit the corresponding Journal Entry Vouchers (JEVs) for adjustments made with its supporting documents for verification, if any;
Refrain from granting cash advances before previous cash advances have been settled and liquidated; and
Ensure thereafter that cash advances are fully liquidated at the end of the year and any cash advances that remained unused for a period of two months are returned or refunded immediately to the City Treasurer.

We recommended that management take the following actions:
The CBO, in coordination with the City Peace and Order Council (CPOC), to expedite the retrieval of the transmittal letters for the liquidation reports and the acknowledgment receipts from PHLPost, in order to provide proof that the liquidation documents of the cash advances for confidential expenses have been submitted and transmitted to the COA Chairman;
The CPOC to convene and address this matter and exert earnest efforts to liquidate the long-outstanding cash advances for Confidential Funds, in the event that no liquidation has been made;
Management to make representation with the Office of the COA Chairperson to confirm receipt of the liquidation reports and request information on the status of audit and issuance the corresponding Credit Advices, by presenting copies of the transmittal letters and acknowledgment receipts from PHLPost (if retrieved), in order to expedite the process;
The CAO to:
Submit the JEVs for any adjustments or entries made to record the liquidation to the COA auditor’s office, ensuring that they are duly supported by Credit Notices or other proof that the Office of the COA Chairman has received the liquidation reports and found these in order; and
Make adequate disclosures in the Notes to Financial Statements.

We recommended that management:
Submit a written justification for not imposing the three-strike rule and contract termination for the "Concreting of Jct. Brgy Mabuhay to Brgy Banlag proper to Sitio Pantaron FMR" project, in compliance with the IMA and the Operations Manual, supported by relevant documentation.
Ensure that the LGU complies with its contractual obligations under the IMA to implement PRDP subprojects with due diligence and efficiency;
